pageSummary: Hiking 26 miles of the Northumbrian coast because of their support in memory of our dad/granddad
pageSummaryWhat: Hiking 26 miles of the Northumbrian coast
pageSummaryWhy: of their support in memory of our dad/granddad
story:
Thanks for supporting our fundraising in memory of Alun Woodward, our beloved and dearly missed Dad and Granddad. Alun died on 26 April 2020 from lung cancer. Macmillan Cancer Support were there to help both him and our Mum/Nana to help him live as fully as he could, in a time when lockdown prevented him from doing many of the things he would have wanted in his final weeks. 

Aaryn and Rach are going to hike the 26 miles from Alnwick Castle to Bamburgh in one day, passing through many of the places Alun frequented and loved along the way. The Northumbrian coast was special to him and is even more so to our family now he is gone. We cannot think of a more fitting way to remember him and raise money for those who supported us all in the process. Any amount, no matter how big or small, will make such a massive difference and ensure that all families continue to receive the support they need at such an uncertain and often sad time. Thank you, thank you, thank you for supporting us. Huge virtual hugs and kisses. 

(So whatever cancer throws your way, Macmillan Cancer Support are right there with you. Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.)

story:
Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. 

Recently as a family we experienced first hand the devastation cancer causes, sadly losing our beloved Bampa. Seeing the work done first hand by Macmillan and the huge impact they can have on the fight against cancer, and during the current climate where cancer screenings and treatments seem to be negatively affected by the Corona Virus outbreak I am going to be running the Cardiff Half Marathon on behalf of the Macmillan Cancer Support Team. 

No mater how big or small a donation will be greatly appreciated by myself and will go a long way in supporting Macmillan Team to continue the great work they do in the fight against cancer and the support they offer to the families devastated by this disease.

pageSummary: Macmillan’s #AlphaPet challenge.. because Now more than ever Macmillan needs our help!
pageSummaryWhy: Now more than ever Macmillan needs our help!
story:
Macmillan hold a very special place in my heart. 

We have all been affected in one way or another by cancer and now more than ever we need to support the cancer care and support Macmillan provide 

Anyone who knows me will know my biggest hero is my uncle who lost his battle to cancer in 2012, then it came back to bite us again with my little nana (but she kicked it’s backside) and yet again it’s hit us with my Nanny June  (again kicking its backside right out) 

My biggest love is my dogs. So in memory of my Uncle John and all those we have lost, those who beat it and those who continue to fight it, I a  joining the Macmillan AlphaPet challenge. 

We will be going through A-Z snapping pictures of Lulu and Beau with something or somewhere with each letter of the alphabet 

We hope this is a light hearted way to raise some much needed money for Macmillan and spread some cheer during these difficult times


Thank you for reading this and thank you for your donation


Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there

pageSummary: A series of donation-based lunchtime meditations
pageSummaryWhat: A series of donation-based lunchtime meditations
story:
Thank you so much for joining our lunchtime meditation sessions during the November 2020 UK lockdown. The first 12-12.30pm session will be on Thursday November 5; provisionally the final class will be on Wednesday December 2. All sessions will be live streamed over zoom.

Meditation, in all its different forms, is essentially a practical, powerful form of self-care. At Yoga at the Mill we love delivering meditation and always aim to teach in a nurturing, gentle, entirely secular way. 

Rest assured there is no need to sit crossed legged (unless you would like to!) or clear your mind of thoughts (impossible!).

All practices will be for ANYBODY and will help us gently de-tangle from the human mind's continual narratives, into a felt awareness of the body.

If you have enjoyed the sessions, or found them worthwhile, please consider offering a donation here. If each student attending chose to donate £5 for each session attended, we could collectively raise £750 upwards for Macmillan over a period of four weeks. 

Thank you so much for your presence and support.
title: Yoga at the Mill's lunchtime meditation series, November 2020

story:
To mark the start of the second lockdown myself and my Husband, Rob, along with my Mum and Dad are taking on this challenge; each to run 5km everyday for 10 days. We will be completing our runs separately due to the current restrictions, but will be providing support to each other virtually! The first run starts on Monday 9th November!

We have all enjoyed running for many years now, however running everyday will certainly be a challenge! Especially finding the time and enthusiasm to run when we have a 3 month old baby!! 

This is also a great month for my parents to challenge themselves with my Mum turning 60 this month, and them both celebrating their 40th wedding anniversary. 

Cancer has affected people we know and love in the past and we all have people close to us who are currently suffering with this awful diagnosis.

Therefore now more than ever we feel we want to do our bit to raise money for a charity that we really care about whilst personally challenging ourselves!

pageSummary: Raising £2020 by running 2020km in 2020 because of the £175m fundraising shortfall due to COVID
pageSummaryWhy: of the £175m fundraising shortfall due to COVID
story:
Can I run 2020km in 2020? 

5.5km per day 

39km per week

168km per month

So far so good……………1759km into the challenge with 261km to
go.

I started this challenge as a personal one but would love to
raise £2020 for a charity that is close to my heart, MacMillian Cancer Support.

I’ve seen first-hand the amazing work they do and was
shocked to hear they will have to make 300+ people redundant due to a potential £175 million fundraising loss by 2022.

Please help me raise £2020 this year to recognise the
support they gave to my mother in law, Jennifer and many others affected by cancer.

You can follow my progress on Strava: https://www.strava.com/athletes/47804878
title: Running 2020km in 2020

pageSummary: In memory of our girl Kelly
pageSummaryWhat: In memory of our girl Kelly
story:
Many of you will know in 2020 this year my beautiful sister Kelly passed away with extensive heart disease, she only had 25% function left in her heart and we will never know how she still got up and looked after her 3 babies but every day she did!

She left behind 4 beautiful strong amazing children and we want to help anyone else going through this awful disease

We would love to raise money for something that is so so close to our hearts and to help others going through this.

We truly believe with funding and support from the public we can find a cure for this and keep our families safe

Me and my wonderful sisters friends will be sky diving and covering the costs so all monies raised will go to The British Heart Foundation for our stunning girl.





Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

pageSummary: Trying to cover 2193km under my own power
pageSummaryWhat: Trying to cover 2193km under my own power
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

As many of you aware it has been a hell-ish 12 months. 

I decided that despite the pandemic I wanted to do something a little more epic than usual before the end of 2021. I wanted this year to be memorable for reasons that are not at all hell-ish. 

Therefore I have decided to try and cover the distance from hell to home. (It turns out Hell is a small town in Norway) at 2193Km this is a large undertaking for me and I hope that it inspires you to donate anything you can afford to this very worthwhile cause. 

I will be posting regular updates on my runs/walks/obstacle courses and I hope that they cause amusement or maybe even a little inspiration. 


Thank you for your time, come back soon for more updates. 


Sam
title: Samuel's Covering 2193km before the end of 2021

story:
Thanks for visiting our page. We're raising money for the British Heart Foundation and would be so grateful for your support. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
eventName: Spalding GD 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs
this Christmas!

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Spalding group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community.

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this
festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships!

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss,
social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs
this Christmas!

During December the four-legged volunteers of the  Newmarket group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community. 

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this
festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships! 

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas. 

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss,
social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas
title: Newmarket 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas

charity.description: The ability to get around is vital in order to live a full life yet thousands of people with sight loss never leave home alone. We empower visually impaired people to do that and rely on the support of the public to fund the guide dog service.
charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
eventName: Tyne Delta 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas
story:
The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas Collection

Help us as we aim to raise enough to support 12 brand new guide dogs
this Christmas!

During December the four-legged volunteers of the Tyne Delta group would usually be out and about wagging their tails and meeting you at collections and events in your community.

Due to the current situation, we’re not able to be out as much this
festive season, and we know you will miss seeing our life-changing doggy volunteers! We’re hoping you will help us and donate to our ‘12 Guide Dogs of Christmas’ Collection as we aim to raise enough for 12 new guide dog partnerships!

It costs over £56,000 to fund the lifetime cost of a guide dog. Please consider donating £12 during our 12-day collection so we can fund 12 new life-changers this Christmas.

We appreciate that times are difficult, but for people with sight loss,
social isolation can be their everyday. You can help them feel less alone, now and in the future.

Don’t forget to send it on through Facebook, WhatsApp, email or text and get your friends and family involved too.

Thank you and Merry Christmas
title: Tyne Delta 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Cancer Research, Needs us now RIGHT NOW!!! 9.6 Million people die from Cancer each year! This is too many people In the Uk over 165,000 cancer deaths happen annually! #fightcancer #100kburpeechallenge


We are all going through shifting seasons, then COVID 19 disrupted progress for us all, during the peak of the first lockdown you may have found yourself depressed because of the set backs and adversity caused by the virus, now imagine you are a cancer patient with all that stress and the impending fear of what could happen next! Or imagine you was so scared you didn’t go for that scan or check up because you didn’t have good clear advice about what cancer may look like, the advice which could have saved your life if addressed early on!


Cancer services need to remain open and Cancer Research is forever improving because of its importance for future generations, but valuable funding is needed to undertake more research and make breakthroughs and we will get over this adversity together only when we work together towards one goal, that’s when I decided to create a challenge, a challenge to fight poor health, it’s time to make a better future for the next generations and lead by example!


Within us all is a rich capacity, and some of us never get to reach that potential because they are taken away from us far far too early!
“A Journey of Thousand miles begins with a single step - Lao Tzu”

So a journey of 100k burpees begins with a single burpee, so here we go...
Burpee 1/100,000 Burpees


Www.justgiving.com/fundraising/100k-Burpees


#firststeps #challenge #burpees #fundraiser #charityfundraiser #decidetowin #takingownership
#cancerresearch #cancerresearchuk


This is my first ever solo fundraiser, I have set no time limit to complete my burpees by as I have never done any type of challenge on this scale, this is a mountain of a challenge for me someone who eats unhealthy and is overweight but I will be recording all my progress and aim to complete as soon as possible to help Cancer Research get the funding it needs!


Also every pound donated I will match up-to the first £1000*, adding a maximum of £1000 to the end figure if donations exceed the goal.

story:
Hello and welcome to my just giving page!

Here's a little insight to what this is and why I'm doing it....

Casting for a cure is an annual carp fishing competition that I initially set up in 2016. The original competition consisted of a few friends, but has grown slightly over the years with new friends being made. Since its beginning we have raise over £1000 for cancer research, and we have no intention of stopping there. Raising money is no easy task as the competition only raises so much. So we also have other events like table top sales, raffles and tombolas. 

Why do we do it?......

There's not many people I've met that haven't been affected by cancer in one way or another! Whether this be directly, or someone they know etc..  

I've had people very close to me battle cancer, one of which was an angler that took part in this competition, who unfortunately lost his fight.

If you can spare anything, even just £1..... it will make a big difference! Together we can help fund the fight against cancer. The scientists and researchers have come so far, and it's thanks to them so many people are still here today. 

PLEASE........ help us help them.

This year is the competitions 5th year anniversary! I've set a huge target of £1000 and need your help to help me reach it xxx

story:
On the 2nd of November I decided to donate 12 inches of my hair to the Little Princess Trust. This organisation manufactures wigs. They are a brilliant non profit  who supply the best real hair wigs to children and young people up to 24 who have lost their hair to cancer treatments and other illnesses. Being 20 myself this is very personal. Along side this I will also be aiming to raise £500 to go directly to cancer research from this hair cut. My family have had an on going battle with many different forms of cancer and I want to do as much as I can to benefit this amazing charity. In particular, Ive done this for my grandparents, aunt and uncle who have died of cancer, and everyone else who has battled the horrendous disease. I’d rather my hair go to someone in need and give to an amazing cause. 

All support and help would be greatly appreciated. Thank you so so much.

story:
Raffle tickets will be £2 and you could win a Bobyshop bundle worth £43! Even if you cant make it on Friday you can still enter 

To enter just donate (by tapping below) and your name will be entered into the draw. We will reveal the winner on Friday, 6th November 2020

This year has been rubbish for all of us but for some it has been devistating and that is an understatement.

We all know someone who has won or lost their cancer battles. We need get this disease under control and we can help by donating money to Cancer Research.

Just £5 can kit out a lab with the essential chemicals needed for their research 

£25 funds a specialist nurse for 1 hour and £50 gets a scientific sieve that enables the scientists to seperate the small and large DNA 🧬 and reveal vital clues on how cancer works.

They cant do this without the support from us!

pageSummary: I will be setting myself 4 challenges in November because Cancer doesn’t stop during a Pandemic
pageSummaryWhat: I will be setting myself 4 challenges in November
pageSummaryWhy: Cancer doesn’t stop during a Pandemic
story:
I will be raising money once again for Cancer Research. 

Cancer hasn’t stopped because of COVID-19

The story

My Mum was diagnosed with breast cancer, and after several operations and treatments was given the all clear by the doctor. We continued as a family to live our lives for several years thinking she was cancer free when cancer struck for a second time. This time leaving it’s mark by making my mum terminally ill. Unfortunately, after all that treatment the doctors missed that the cancer had spread to other parts of the body, meaning it is incurable. We are in our final option of the delay process which is chemotherapy (and it is a nasty piece of shit). Myself and my family continue to fight this day in and out. I am not only doing this for my mum but for everyone affected by Cancer.

To continue the fight I have decided to come up with 4 weekly challenges in no particular order to raise money and awareness: 

Week 1 - Head Shave 

Week 2 - Cycle from Nottingham to Mansfield 

Week 3 - Half Marathon 

Week 4 - 24 hours without food

I don’t know how my body will adapt to these challenges. I can’t remember the last time I had my head shaved let alone go without food for a day. This will be a physical and emotional battle, therefore, I will need the support of my friends and family.

2020 hasn’t been easy, but all I know is that Cancer doesn’t stop through a pandemic.

Thanks to the unconditional support of my friends and family I have been able to beat every fundraising target in the past. This time I hope to do the same.

If anyone would like to join me or take part please get in touch!

Finally, I also urge for you check yourself. The earlier you find it, the better your chances. If you’re unsure seek medical advice.

Floyd :)

story:
Festive Dip

Dip to Deliver Care

7 Days to Donate £7 and Nominate 7 Friends to raise £7,000

Help us deliver care this festive period by taking a ‘Dip’.  The choice of
how you do this is entirely up to you – You can get your wellies on or go bare footed. Jump in puddles, a bucket of ice or head for a splash in the sea. 
If you’re feeling full of beans, then get in a bath of beans. 

The challenge lasts from 26th December 2020 to 1st January 2021.  

A great time to make and share special memories with your family or
friends.

Whatever you do have a great time and please share all your crazy pictures and videos on our Facebook event page

story:
Lloyds Banking Group's CIC team are once again pulling on their trainers in anticipation of the Walk to Singapore fundraiser for Marie Curie! Over November, up to 400 colleagues will be walking, running and cycling X miles to the office in Singapore, logging their efforts through Strava.

Donate to participate, leaving your name and department so we can announce who has raised the most. 

At Marie Curie, everything we do from providing expert care and funding ground-breaking research to providing practical information and emotional support, helps dying people and their loved ones to make the most of the time they have together.

The pandemic has increased the need for our services and for Marie Curie and those we support, the crisis is not lifting. We predict that demand for our services will in fact continue to rise. By pledging your support, you will help us meet this demand and be there for people when they need us. 

On behalf of each and every one of us here at Marie Curie, thank you for your support!
title: Team CIC's Walk to Singapore

story:
I have set myself the physical challenge of climbing Mount Kilimanjaro in Tanzania in September 2021.

I will be raising money for two separate charities. The first will be the British Lung Foundation, in memory of my grandad Bill who passed away in July 2020 after his fight with COPD. The second charity will be Marie Curie in memory of my grandad Ken who passed away in August 2020 following his fight with prostate cancer.

Any donations would be massively appreciated. Thank you, Beth xx

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.
charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.
title: Susan

charity.description: Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders (MSF) is the world's leading medical humanitarian aid organisation. We work in over 70 countries - in conflict zones, natural disasters and epidemics. We are independent, neutral and impartial. We provide medical care where it's needed most.
charity.name: Medecins Sans Frontieres / Doctors Without Borders (MSF)
story: MSF's emergency teams are experts at fighting disease outbreaks. I'm raising funds to support the medical teams on the ground as they respond to the coronavirus crisis. Right now, MSF is providing urgently needed medical care and support in more than 70 countries to counter the coronavirus disease. MSF's medical teams are also gearing up to confront potential outbreaks in the hundreds of areas they were already working before the pandemic struck. MSF are deploying medics, sending supplies and applying nearly 50 years of experience fighting epidemics to protect the most vulnerable and save lives. How you can help: - £16 can pay for a surgical tunic, trousers and a pair of sterile reusable gloves. - £28 can pay for protective plastic goggles for four doctors. - £58 can pay for sterile gloves for 30 medics. - £110 can pay for five protective suits to keep staff safe. Thank you.
title: Chris’s page

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
charity.registrationNumber: 288701 (England and Wales) and SC039479 (Scotland)
story:
Clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene should be a normal part of everyone’s daily life. 

Without all three, people can’t live dignified, healthy lives. With all three, they can unlock their potential, break free from poverty and change their lives for good.

With clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene, children are born healthier. They get the chance to go to school and grow up to become adults. Women and men get to earn a living. Whole communities start to thrive. 

It sounds normal and it should be.
title: Kyle's Brew at Home: WaterAid Fundraiser
